footer: footer.title: {[TimesNewRoman x 9]}{[7.97 x 7, 5.978 x 2]}{[normal x 9]}{[null x 7, italic x 2]} //Note: For survival data, the mean, 10%, and maximum (last animal to die) survival were obtained from the data used to generate the curves presented in Figure 2A. A standard Student’s t-test was used to statistically analyze the mean survival, and the statistical analysis of the 10% survival (when 90% of the rats died) was conducted as described by Wang et al.^{19} using the Boschloo test. ^{a Significantly different from the AL group (P < 0.001);} ^{b significantly different from the 10% DR group (P = 0.016).} For the Gompertz data, the Gompertz parameters A and B are the initial rate of mortality and the rate of increase in the hazard for mortality (i.e., the mortality rate), respectively. The values shown are the estimates of each parameter with the lower and upper confidence intervals.
